<font color="#FF0000">WHAT CAN I SAY? + ON GUARD?</font><br>
<tt>Fri Aug 22  1:02:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Edward,<br>
     While I may argue hard on points that bother me; I do understand that Cook, you and the others have very deepseated reasons and feelings behind the way you all express yourselves.  It is not worth it to me to win a point, no matter how right I may or may not be, if by the means I do so, I tear open old wounds that have been in the slow process of healing.  I won't pretend I can really feel your pain, but I can see with my heart that it is there, try to give what poor comfort I'm able and if nothing else be present to bear witness.  <br><br>
Cook,<br>
     Can't believe you got out of guard duty initially.  Before I made 1LT, I had to pull time on our unit's assigned guard tower located opposite the neughboring village's shit field...and I mean just that!  Just after sunrise, a bunch of villagers would come out, squat and take a dump.  About the time we left for the day, a guy with a bucket would be out there scooping it up for later application in the paddies and fields.  I can just hear the guffaws over the suitability of that post for a MI company.  Anyway, never forgot Christmas Eve near midnight when an overloaded jeep from my unit pulled up bellowing slightly off key Christmas carols 
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


